Here’s how to implement a Mastra agent that **(1) can call tools** and **(2) maintains conversation state across turns using memory**.

---

## 1. Create a tool

```ts
import { createTool } from "@mastra/core/tools";
import { z } from "zod";

export const addTool = createTool({
  id: "add-tool",
  description: "Adds two numbers",
  inputSchema: z.object({
    a: z.number(),
    b: z.number(),
  }),
  outputSchema: z.object({
    result: z.number(),
  }),
  execute: async ({ a, b }) => {
    return { result: a + b };
  },
});
```

---

## 2. Add the tool to an agent

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { addTool } from "../tools/add-tool";
import { Memory } from "@mastra/memory";

export const mathAgent = new Agent({
  id: "math-agent",
  name: "Math Agent",
  instructions: `
    You are a math assistant. Use the addTool when users ask to add numbers.
  `,
  model: "openai/gpt-5.1",
  tools: { addTool },
  memory: new Memory({
    options: { lastMessages: 20 },
  }),
});
```

---

## 3. Add storage to Mastra (required for memory persistence)

```ts
import { Mastra } from "@mastra/core";
import { LibSQLStore } from "@mastra/libsql";
import { mathAgent } from "./agents/math-agent";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: { mathAgent },
  storage: new LibSQLStore({
    id: "app-storage",
    url: ":memory:", // replace with a real DB in production
  }),
});
```

---

## 4. Maintain conversation state across turns

Use consistent **resource** and **thread** IDs:

```ts
const agent = mastra.getAgent("mathAgent");

// Turn 1
await agent.generate("Remember that my number is 5.", {
  memory: {
    resource: "user-123",
    thread: "session-123",
  },
});

// Turn 2
const result = await agent.generate(
  "Add my number to 7 using the tool.",
  {
    memory: {
      resource: "user-123",
      thread: "session-123",
    },
  }
);

console.log(result.text);
```

The agent will recall the earlier message ("my number is 5") and can use `addTool` to compute 5 + 7.

